	<p>On the background of wartime and postwar scarcity competition and opposition in sports was not as important as during peacetime. And so sport were then seen as most of all a kind of leisure, as a way of returning to normal life, even if not for long.</p>
	<p>Sports played a special role in the various forced labor camps where prisoners of war were held. Simple kinds of sports that did not require special equipment offered prisoners one of the only ways of relaxing from their difficult reality, to attempt to recall their lost life from before the war. Camp officials, as a rule, tolerated the athletic enthusiasm of the prisoners. Such games, therefore, were often used as a cover for forbidden activity—communication with other groups of prisoners or even escape.</p>
	<p>"(S)ports between Ukrainian prisoners ...filled an important function of moral support in the unenviable everyday life of the prisoners of war and were a first-rate help for mutual knowledge and becoming closer with representatives of other peoples and threw not once clear rays of hope in the darkness of camp life behind the wires." Ievhen Birchak, organizer of Ukrainian sport movement in DP camps (Almanac of the Council of Physical Culture,  Munich, 1951)</p>
	
	<h4>Displaced Sports</h4>
