	<p>Even after the cessation of hostilities Europe still suffered the consequences of the war for a long time. The peripatetic quality of wartime drove huge masses of Ukrainians, Poles, Lithuanians, Estonians, and other exiles from East Central Europe away from their native cities. They all ended up in displaced persons camps organized by the allied troops. Forced to live in these camps for several years, the displaced persons organized schools, social organizations and, of course, sports teams. For people who had lost their homes, their families and their homelands, sports were not just leisure, but an important instrument in declaring normality and humanity. An important gesture was the introduction in various cities in Germany of the "Displaced Persons Olympiad." This event took place in summer-fall of 1948—together with the Olympic Games in London. In this way, the organizers, the International Committee of Political Refugees, wanted to attract the world public's attention and prove their legitimacy.</p>
	<p>"… These games will be no competition for the Great Olympiad, they do not even have this inclination. They will only be only another proof of the solidarity of members of the oppressed nations exiled from their homelands, they must be a proof of their moral and physical skill." (Oleh Lysiak, sports journalist (Almanac of the Council of Physical Culture, Munich, 1953)</p>
	<p>It is possible that it was at the camp Olympiad that the anthem "Ukraine has not yet perished" rang out for the first time before the start of a competition. Ukrainians showed their best results in football, easily defeating the other finalists—Poles and Lithuanians.</p>
	
	<h4>"The Olympic Spirit" Behind Barbed Wire</h4>
