              <p class="big-title">Map showing the routes of "white couriers" (from Tadeusz Chciuk, White Couriers, Munich, 1986)</p>
              </div>            
            </div>
    </div>
	<p>The goal of athletic paramilitary organizations was the preparation of members for possible war. With the approach of real hostilities these former athletes became soldiers and fought against their enemies in direct—not athletic—methods. However, their good physical condition gave them clear advantage above other fighters. It was not uncommon for people connected with sports to be given special tasks—skiers and runners became couriers, shooters became snipers, parachutists became saboteurs behind the frontlines in the rear.</p>
	<p>In a different form, paramilitary athletic organizations during the war gave even young people an opportunity to express themselves. Well-known is the example of the scouting group "White Couriers" (Biali kurierzy) created on the base of junior Polish civil military athletic club "Junak," which was active in interwar Drohobych. After the arrival of Soviet power in western Ukraine young athletes, using their athletic skills, helped people cross the Hungarian border. On their return the "white couriers" delivered to the Polish underground money and information.</p>
	
